|1925
|Child Welfare Act 1925
| In 1925, [[Reform Government of New Zealand|The Reform Government of New Zealand]] passed the Child Welfare Act 1925. This Act established the Child Welfare Division, which was responsible for deprived and delinquent children.<ref>[http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/childhood/page-6#ref1 "Welfare rights"], "Teara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand." Retrieved 5/2/14.</ref> 
|-
|1959
|[[United Nations]] 
|As part of a growing [[Children's rights movement|movement on children's rights]], the [[United Nations General Assembly]] adopted an expanded version of the [[Declaration of the Rights of the Child]], which was originally drafted by [[Save the Children]] founder, [[Eglantyne Jebb]] in 1923. New Zealand was a member of the United Nations at this time.<ref>[https://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/RES/1386(XIV)&Lang=E&Area=RESOLUTION "Declaration on the Rights of the Child"], United Nations General Assembly Resolution 1386 [XIV]. 20 November 1959.</ref> 
|-
| 1968
| Guardianship Act 1968
| The Guardianship Act 1968 defined and regulated the authority of parents as guardians. More importantly, it gave children paramount welfare status above other considerations, including parent's rights.<ref>[http://legislation.knowledge-basket.co.nz/gpacts/reprint/text/1968/an/063.html Guardianship Act 1968, s 23], "LegislationNZ." Retrieved 5/3/14.</ref>
|-
| 1969 
| Status of Children Act 1969
| The Status of Children Act 1969 gave equal status to minors, regardless of their country of birth or the marital status of their parents.<ref>[http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1969/0018/latest/whole.html Status of Children Act 1969, s 3 ], "New Zealand Legislation." Retrieved 5/3/14.</ref>
|-
| 1990
| New Zealand Bill of Rights 1990
| The New Zealand Bill of Rights 1990 prohibited discrimination on the grounds of age (applicable only to those 16 years or over).<ref>[http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1990/0109/latest/DLM224792.html New Zealand Bill of Rights Act 1990, s 19] "New Zealand Legislation." Retrieved 4/2/14.</ref><ref>[http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1993/0082/latest/DLM304212.html Human Rights Act 1993, s 21], "New Zealand Legislation." Retrieved 5/2/14.</ref>
|-
|1993
| United Nations
| New Zealand ratified the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Children (UNCRC)
|-
